**Research Questions**

1. **Inspect the default test project structure created in the Activity. Describe the purpose for each of the folders of the following in the project structure: node\_modules, src, src/app, src/assets, and src/environments.**

In an Angular project, several important folders are created to organize the structure and functionality of the application. The node\_modules folder contains all the installed libraries and packages that the application needs to function properly; it is automatically managed by npm (Node Package Manager). The src folder is where all of the actual source code for the application is located, including components, services, and assets. Inside src, the src/app folder specifically holds the application logic, including the components, modules, services, and routing configurations. The src/assets folder is intended for static assets such as images, stylesheets, and fonts that the application might need. The src/environments folder contains environment configuration files like environment.ts for development and environment.prod.ts for production; these files allow you to define settings based on the build environment.

2. **Describe the purpose for each of the following files in the project: angular.json, package.json, and tsconfig.json.**

 Several key files are created when setting up an Angular project. The angular.json file is a critical configuration file that defines how the Angular CLI should build and serve the application, including options for styling, assets, and optimization settings. The package.json file serves as a manifest for the project, listing all the npm packages the project depends on, as well as defining project metadata and script commands for tasks like starting the server or running tests. The tsconfig.json file contains the TypeScript compiler options, which tell the compiler how to interpret the TypeScript code, including module types, target JavaScript versions, and path aliases. Each of these files plays a major role in making sure that the Angular application can be developed, built, and deployed properly.

3. **Inspect the page source for the default page displayed when running the test project. Explain how the resultant page was generated by Angular by providing a brief overview and purpose for each of the following files: main.ts, app.component.css, app.component.html, app.component.ts, and app.module.ts.**

 When running an Angular application, the displayed webpage is generated through a collaboration of several important files. The main.ts file is the entry point of the application; it bootstraps the root module (AppModule) which launches the app. The app.component.ts file defines the TypeScript logic behind the main component, including properties and functions that are bound to the view. The app.component.html file contains the actual HTML template of the main component, rendering the layout and binding to the variables defined in the TypeScript class. The app.component.css file provides specific CSS styling rules for the app.component.html to maintain consistent appearance and visual structure. Finally, the app.module.ts file defines the applicationâ€™s root module, registering all components and modules that the app will use, and ensuring that Angular knows how to load and organize them correctly. Together, these files dynamically render and manage the content displayed in the browser.
